[{"x0": 67.75, "y0": 4.85, "x1": 81.94, "y1": 6.84}, {"x0": 7.32, "y0": 4.93, "x1": 39.85, "y1": 7.12}, {"x0": 45.64, "y0": 0.9, "x1": 53.77, "y1": 6.96}, {"x0": 61.29, "y0": 2.1, "x1": 67.96, "y1": 6.81}, {"x0": 14.7, "y0": 11.37, "x1": 39.58, "y1": 28.6}, {"x0": 44.2, "y0": 11.36, "x1": 79.26, "y1": 28.27}, {"x0": 19.06, "y0": 40.84, "x1": 76.55, "y1": 61.18}], "full_text": "Radiology\n◦ Inability to assess extra-cardiac pathology.\nGrey scale Colour Doppler\nRadioisotope Study (Thallium)\nThis nuclear medicine technique is specifically used to detect myocardial viability.\n• Mechanism: Normal areas show tracer uptake; ischemic areas present as defects.\n• Limitation: Involves exposure to radioactive materials.\nCardiac CT\nCardiac CT provides high spatial resolution and multiplanar capability, including 3D\nreconstructions.\nFeature Details\n-Excellent anatomical detail\nAdvantages -Simultaneous examination of the heart and coronary arteries\n-Assessment of cardiac structure, function, and extra-cardiac problems.\n-Exposure to ionizing radiation\nDisadvantages -Requires contrast media (with potential hazards)\n-limited information about tissue viability.\nOther benefits: -Determining Calcium score\n-Tracing the vessels\nCalcium score\n83"}